g.title: Folded Corner
g.desc: The Builder pattern enables ‘fine’ control over the product c...

g.text: The Builder pattern enables ‘fine’ control over the product creation. This means, it is possible to perform a creation step, process something else and perform another creation step. After all creation steps are done, the product is returned. This is different from the Factory patterns. The Factory patterns create a product and return it immediately. Often the product exposes its internals to allow the step-by-step creation. This means a client could perform these constructions steps. However, this might endanger the validity of the product. A constraint could be that missing a construction step or calling them in the wrong order, results in an invalid product. The Builder pattern could verify this validity before returning the product to the client.

g.title: Folded Corner.15
g.desc: The Builder pattern compliments the Single Responsibility Pri...

g.text: The Builder pattern compliments the Single Responsibility Principle by separating construction logic and representation. This enables reusability and readability. Reusability, because different product representations can be created with the same construction algorithm. Readability, because the Builder logic is extracted from the client. Client is not ‘polluted’ with sequential creation steps or validity checks.

g.title: Folded Corner.20
g.desc: The Builder pattern compliments the Open Closed Principle by ...

g.text: The Builder pattern compliments the Open Closed Principle by separating construction logic and representation via an abstraction. This enables stability. Stability, because new representations (=Builders) can be added without modifying the construction algorithm (=Director) directly.

g.title: Folded Corner.41
g.desc: The Builder pattern enables abstracting away and preventing c...

g.text: The Builder pattern enables abstracting away and preventing constructor telescoping. Constructor telescoping is overloading the constructor of the product to create different variants. The disadvantage of this approach is that it makes usability and readability harder. Clients need to remember the order of the parameter set and which constructor to call for the specific variant. Refactoring the code could result in Setters on the product. This could then be used by the Builder pattern to create the product in a safe-way. However, often code cannot be changed, because legacy parts are depend on the implementation. The Builder pattern can provide a simplified interface, on top of the telescope constructors, towards new clients.

g.text: The same construction logic applies to different representations

g.title: Folded Corner.53
g.desc: The main ‘goal’ of the Builder pattern is to re-use the same ...

g.text: The main ‘goal’ of the Builder pattern is to re-use the same construction logic for different representations. The products that can be constructed by the same algorithm could be very different in their interface. The Builder (class) unifies these interfaces by serving as a kind of Adapter (=wrapper) between the builder interface and the product interface. This enables the Director to re-use identical construction steps on different Builders. Builders are then responsible for constructing different representations and enable the client to retrieve the final product.

g.title: Rectangle.56
g.desc: The same construction logic applies to multiple clients
g.text: The same construction logic applies to multiple clients

g.title: Folded Corner.95
g.desc: The Builder pattern enables re-use of the same construction s...

g.text: The Builder pattern enables re-use of the same construction steps across multiple clients. The Director class bundles the product construction steps overcoming clients to duplicate that construction algorithm. The necessity of the Builder class could be debatable when there is only a single representation that needs to be created. It could be chosen to distribute Builder logic across the product and Director. The product provides setters (JavaBeans Pattern) and the Director ‘guards’ the product until it is constructed. However, this brings us close to implementing a Simple Factory, except that the ‘full’ construction of the product is on a step-by-step base.

g.text: The flexibility that the Builder Pattern provides via the Open Closed Principle comes with a down-side. The concrete builder and interface provide a form of indirection. Indirection makes the code harder to comprehend, navigate and debug.

g.text: The reusability that the Builder Pattern provides, via the Single Responsibility Principle, comes with a disadvantage. The separation of representation and construction algorithm causes the build logic to be more scattered. This has negative impact on readability of the code.
